Sara and Ben like to play with paper and crayons. They draw pictures of animals, flowers and cars. Sometimes they cut out their pictures and make cards for their mom and dad.

One day, Sara and Ben find a big box of paper in the garage. It is different from the paper they usually use. It is thick and rough and has lines on it. Sara and Ben wonder what it is.

They ask their dad, who is working on his computer. He says, "That is lumber paper. It is made from trees. I use it to print my work."

Sara and Ben are curious. They ask, "What is print?"

Dad says, "Print is when you make words and pictures on paper with a machine. Like this." He shows them his printer, which is black and noisy. He presses a button and a paper comes out. It has words and graphs on it.

Sara and Ben think it is boring. They say, "Can we print our pictures on the lumber paper?"

Dad says, "Sure, why not? But be careful, the lumber paper is not very smooth. It might jam the printer."

Sara and Ben take some lumber paper and some crayons. They draw their favorite things on it. Sara draws a rainbow and a unicorn. Ben draws a rocket and a dinosaur. They are very proud of their pictures.

They go to the printer and put their lumber paper in it. They press the button and wait. But nothing happens. The printer makes a loud sound and stops. Sara and Ben are scared. They look at the printer and see a red light flashing.

Dad hears the noise and comes to see what is wrong. He sees the lumber paper stuck in the printer. He says, "Oh no, what have you done? You jammed the printer with the lumber paper. Now I have to fix it."

Sara and Ben are sorry. They say, "We are sorry, dad. We wanted to print our pictures on the lumber paper. We did not know it would jam the printer."

Dad is not angry. He says, "It's okay, I understand. You were curious and creative. But next time, ask me before you use the printer. And use regular paper, not lumber paper. Lumber paper is not good for printing."

He takes out the lumber paper and the pictures. He says, "These are very nice pictures. You are good artists. Why don't you hang them on the wall?"

Sara and Ben are happy. They say, "Thank you, dad. We love you."

They hug their dad and hang their pictures on the wall. They look at them and smile. They like their lumber paper art.
<|end|>


