Tim and Sue liked to play in the woods. They liked to run, jump, and hide. One day, they saw a big hole in the ground. It was a well. They went near it and looked down. It was very dark and deep.

"Let's throw a stone and see how long it takes to splash," Tim said. He picked up a small stone and threw it in the well. They waited and waited, but they did not hear a splash. "Maybe it's too far," Sue said. "Let's try a bigger stone."

They looked around and found a big stone. It was heavy and hard. Tim lifted it with both hands and threw it in the well. They waited and waited, but they did not hear a splash. "Maybe it's too quiet," Sue said. "Let's try a louder thing."

They looked around and found a metal can. It was shiny and noisy. Tim kicked it with his foot and it rolled to the well. He pushed it in with his stick. They waited and waited, but they did not hear a splash. They heard a loud bark.

They looked at each other and felt scared. They had thrown the can on a dog. The dog was in the well. The dog was angry and troubled. It wanted to get out. It barked and barked and barked.

Tim and Sue ran away from the well. They ran to their home. They told their mom and dad what they had done. Their mom and dad were not happy. They called the fireman. The fireman came and got the dog out of the well. The dog was wet and dirty, but it was not hurt. The dog's owner came and thanked the fireman. He was not happy with Tim and Sue. He told them to never play near the well again. Tim and Sue said they were sorry. They learned their lesson. They never played near the well again.
<|end|>


