Lily and Ben were friends. They liked to play in the park. One day, they saw a big nest in a tree. They wanted to see what was inside.

"Let's climb the tree and look at the nest," said Ben.

"OK, but be careful," said Lily.

They climbed the tree and reached the nest. They saw four blue eggs inside. They were very pretty.

"Wow, look at the eggs!" said Ben. "I wonder what kind of birds they are."

"Maybe they are robins, or bluebirds, or jays," said Lily.

"Can I touch one?" asked Ben.

"No, don't touch them!" said Lily. "You might break them, or make the mother bird angry."

But Ben did not listen. He reached out his hand and touched one of the eggs. He felt it was warm and smooth. He wanted to hold it.

He tried to pick up the egg, but it was slippery. He dropped it. The egg fell to the ground and broke. They heard a loud crack.

"Oh no!" said Lily. "You broke the egg!"

Ben felt bad. He looked at the broken egg. He saw a baby bird inside. It was wet and still. It did not move or make a sound.

"I'm sorry, I'm sorry," said Ben. "I didn't mean to break it."

But it was too late. The egg was broken, and the baby bird was gone.

They heard a loud squawk. They looked up and saw the mother bird. She was big and angry. She had sharp claws and a long beak. She saw them and flew towards them.

"Run!" said Lily. "She's coming!"

They jumped down from the tree and ran away. The mother bird chased them. She pecked at their heads and scratched their backs. They cried and screamed.

They ran to the gate of the park and got out. The mother bird stopped at the gate and glared at them. She made a loud noise and flew back to her nest.

Lily and Ben were hurt and scared. They had blood and feathers on their clothes. They felt sorry for the broken egg and the baby bird. They wished they had not climbed the tree and touched the nest.

They learned a hard lesson. They should have been brave and left the eggs alone. They should have respected the mother bird and her nest. They should have listened to Lily.
<|end|>


