Tim and Jen are friends. They like to play in the park. One day, they see a big ashtray near a bench. It is full of dirty things.

"Look, Jen, what is this?" Tim asks.

"I don't know, Tim. It looks bad. Let's go away," Jen says.

But Tim is curious. He wants to touch the ashtray. He reaches his hand to it.

"Tim, no! Don't touch it! It is not for kids. It is for grown-ups who smoke. Smoking is bad. It makes you sick and sad," Jen says.

But Tim does not listen. He touches the ashtray. He feels something sharp and hot. He screams. He drops the ashtray. It breaks. The dirty things fall on the ground.

"Tim, are you okay?" Jen asks. She is scared.

"Ow, ow, ow! It hurts! It hurts!" Tim cries. He holds his hand. He has a cut and a burn.

A lady who works in the park hears them. She runs to them. She sees what happened.

"Oh, no! What did you do? You should not play with the ashtray. It is dangerous. Come with me. I will help you," she says.

She takes Tim and Jen to her office. She cleans Tim's hand. She puts a bandage on it. She gives him a hug and a candy.

"Thank you, lady. I am sorry. I was silly. I will not touch the ashtray again," Tim says.

"You are welcome, Tim. I am glad you are okay. But you should listen to your friend. She was right. The ashtray is not for kids. It is for grown-ups who smoke. And smoking is bad. It makes you sick and sad. Do you understand?" she says.

"Yes, lady. I understand. Smoking is bad. I will not smoke when I grow up. And I will listen to Jen. She is a good friend," Tim says.

"Good, Tim. I am proud of you. And you, Jen, you are a good friend. You tried to stop Tim. You cared for him. You are brave and smart," she says.

"Thank you, lady. I am happy. Tim is my friend. I want him to be safe and happy," Jen says.

The lady smiles. She gives them both a hug and a candy. She tells them to go home and tell their parents what happened. She tells them to be careful and to have fun.

Tim and Jen say goodbye to the lady. They hold hands. They walk home. They are friends. They learned a lesson. They will not play with the ashtray again. They will listen to each other. They will be safe and happy.
<|end|>


