<|end|>
<|asst|>
Lily and Tom were friends. They liked to play in the park. One day, they saw a big melon on a bench. It was green and round and looked yummy.

"Let's eat it!" said Tom.

"But it is not ours," said Lily. "Maybe someone left it here by mistake."

"Who cares?" said Tom. "They will not come back. Come on, it is just a melon."

Lily was not sure, but she was hungry. She followed Tom to the bench. They picked up the melon and ran to a corner. They used a stick to break it open. It was red and juicy inside. They ate it with their hands. It was sweet and good.

They did not see the man who came back to the bench. He was looking for his melon. He had bought it for his wife, who was sick. He was very angry when he saw the empty rind and the seeds on the ground. He looked around and saw Lily and Tom. They had melon juice on their faces and clothes.

"Hey, you little thieves!" he shouted. "You stole my melon! How dare you!"

Lily and Tom were scared. They tried to run away, but the man was faster. He caught them and grabbed them by their arms. He was very strong and rough. He dragged them to the park office. He told the park ranger what they had done. The park ranger called their parents.

Lily and Tom were in big trouble. Their parents were very mad at them. They scolded them and took them home. They had to say sorry to the man and his wife. They had to give them a new melon and some money. They had to stay in their rooms for a week. They had no toys, no TV, no games, no fun.

Lily and Tom were very sad. They wished they had not eaten the melon. They wished they had not forgotten to be good. They wished they had been more alert. They learned a hard lesson. They never stole anything again.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Mia liked to watch the sun rise every morning. She would wake up early and go to the window. She would see the sky change from dark to light. She would see the sun peek out from behind the hills. She would see the sun make the clouds pink and orange. She thought the sun was very attractive.

One day, Mia wanted to give the sun a gift. She thought the sun would like a wrap. She found a big scarf in her closet. It was yellow and soft. She thought it looked like the sun. She took the scarf and ran outside. She wanted to throw the scarf to the sun.

But the sun was too high and too far. Mia could not reach the sun. She tried to jump and toss the scarf. She tried to climb on a rock and swing the scarf. She tried to run and fling the scarf. But the scarf always fell to the ground. Mia felt sad and tired.

Then, she saw her mom come out of the house. Her mom smiled and hugged her. Her mom said, "What are you doing, Mia?" Mia said, "I want to give the sun a wrap. But I can't." Her mom said, "That's very sweet of you, Mia. But the sun doesn't need a wrap. The sun is warm and bright. The sun gives us light and heat. The sun is happy to see you every morning."

Her mom said, "You know who would love a wrap? Grandma. Grandma is cold and lonely. Grandma misses you a lot. Grandma would be happy to see you and your wrap." Mia thought about Grandma. She loved Grandma. She wanted to make Grandma happy. She said, "Okay, Mom. Let's go see Grandma. Let's give her the wrap." Her mom said, "Good idea, Mia. Let's go." They got in the car and drove to Grandma's house.

Mia gave Grandma the wrap. Grandma was surprised and delighted. Grandma said, "Thank you, Mia. This is a beautiful wrap. It's so yellow and soft. It reminds me of the sun. And you are my sunshine." Grandma hugged Mia and kissed her. Mia felt warm and happy. She said, "You're welcome, Grandma. I love you." Grandma said, "I love you too, Mia." They sat on the couch and watched the sun set. They saw the sky change from light to dark. They saw the sun hide behind the hills. They saw the sun make the clouds purple and blue. They thought the sun was very attractive.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sara and Ben are friends. They like to walk and talk in the park. One day, they see a big box near a tree. The box has a message on it. The message says: "Do not open. This is a secret."

Sara is nosy. She wants to know what is in the box. She says to Ben: "Let's open the box. Maybe there is something fun inside."

Ben is scared. He says to Sara: "No, we should not open the box. The message says it is a secret. Maybe someone will be angry if we open it."

But Sara does not listen to Ben. She runs to the box and opens it. She sees a big cake with candles. She says: "Wow, look at this cake! It looks yummy. Let's eat some."

Ben follows Sara. He says: "Sara, wait. Maybe this cake is not for us. Maybe it is for someone's birthday."

But Sara does not listen to Ben. She takes a big bite of the cake. She says: "Mmm, this cake is good. You should try some."

Ben takes a small bite of the cake. He says: "It is good, but I feel bad. We should not eat someone else's cake."

Suddenly, they hear a loud voice. The voice says: "Hey, you two! What are you doing with my cake? That was my surprise for my mom's birthday. You ruined it!"

Sara and Ben look up. They see a big boy with a angry face. He is holding a baseball bat. He says: "You are in big trouble. I'm going to teach you a lesson."

Sara and Ben are scared. They drop the cake and run away. But the big boy is faster. He catches them and hits them with the bat. He says: "That's what you get for being nosy and greedy. Now you will never walk and talk in the park again."

Sara and Ben cry and scream. They wish they had listened to the message and to Ben. They wish they had not opened the box. They wish they had not eaten the cake. They wish they had not met the big boy. They wish they had a good ending. But they do not.
<|end|>


