<|asst|>
Lily and Ben are twins who love to play pretend. One day, they decide to make a factory in their backyard. They use cardboard boxes, plastic bottles, and crayons to make machines and products.

"Look, this is my juice machine. It makes juice from apples and oranges," Lily says, showing Ben her creation.

"That's nice, but my car machine is better. It makes cars from cans and wheels," Ben says, pointing to his own invention.

They both think their machines are the best, and they start to argue.

"No, juice is better than cars. Juice is yummy and healthy," Lily insists.

"No, cars are better than juice. Cars are fast and fun," Ben insists.

They keep insisting and insisting, until their mom comes to see what is going on.

"Wow, you two have made a very successful factory. You have so many machines and products. But why are you shouting at each other?" Mom asks.

"Lily and I don't agree. She thinks juice is better than cars, and I think cars are better than juice," Ben explains.

Mom smiles and says, "Well, you know what? You can both be right. Juice and cars are both good things, and you can both like different things. Why don't you share your machines and products, and see what else you can make together?"

Lily and Ben think about it, and they agree. They stop insisting and start sharing. They make more juice and cars, and also some planes, cakes, and hats. They have fun playing with their factory, and they are happy. Mom is proud of them, and she gives them a hug and a kiss.
<|end|>


