Sara and Ben like to play match. They have cards with pictures of animals, fruits, and colors. They put the cards face down and take turns to flip two cards. If the cards have the same picture, they say "match!" and keep them. If the cards have different pictures, they say "no match!" and put them back.

One day, they play match in the garden. It is spring and the flowers are pretty. The sun is warm and the birds are singing. Sara and Ben are happy. They flip the cards and look for matches.

Sara flips a card with a red apple. She flips another card with a yellow banana. "No match!" she says. She puts the cards back.

Ben flips a card with a blue bird. He flips another card with a green frog. "No match!" he says. He puts the cards back.

Sara flips a card with a pink flower. She flips another card with a pink flower. "Match!" she says. She keeps the cards.

Ben flips a card with a brown bear. He flips another card with a brown bear. "Match!" he says. He keeps the cards.

They keep playing until they have no more cards. They count their matches. Sara has six matches. Ben has five matches. Sara wins.

"Yay, I win!" Sara says. She jumps high in the air. She is proud.

"Good job, Sara!" Ben says. He claps his hands. He is not sad. He is a good friend.

They hug and smile. They love to play match. They love spring. They love each other.
<|end|>


