Ben and Sam are friends. They like to play with guns. They have toy guns that make noise and light. They pretend to be cops and robbers. They run and hide and shoot.

One day, they go to the park with their moms. They see a big slide. They want to go on the slide. They take their guns with them. They climb up the ladder. It is difficult. They are not very big. They help each other.

They reach the top of the slide. They see a girl. She is on the slide. She has a doll. She does not want to move. She says, "This is my slide. Go away."

Ben and Sam are angry. They say, "No, this is our slide. You go away." They point their guns at her. They make noise and light. They say, "Bang, bang, you are dead."

The girl is scared. She cries. She drops her doll. She runs to her mom. She says, "Mommy, mommy, they have guns. They are mean."

Ben and Sam are happy. They have the slide. They enjoy the slide. They slide down. They laugh. They say, "We are the best. We have guns. We are not afraid."

Their moms see them. They are not happy. They say, "Ben, Sam, what are you doing? You are not nice. You are not polite. You do not scare other children. You do not play with guns. You say sorry. You give back the doll."

Ben and Sam are sad. They do not want to say sorry. They do not want to give back the doll. They like their guns. They like to play. But they listen to their moms. They say sorry. They give back the doll. They put away their guns.

They learn a lesson. They do not play with guns. They do not scare other children. They play with other toys. They make new friends. They are nice. They are polite. They are happy.
<|end|>


