Lily liked to eat oranges. They were sweet and juicy and made her mouth happy. But sometimes, oranges were hard to open. She had to peel off the skin with her fingers, and it was sticky and tough.

One day, Lily found a big orange in the kitchen. She wanted to eat it, so she took it to the table and tried to peel it. But it was too hard. She pulled and pulled, but the skin did not come off. She struggled with the orange, but it did not help. She felt confused and sad.

She saw her mom in the living room. She ran to her with the orange in her hand. "Mom, mom, help me!" she cried. "I can't open the orange!"

Her mom smiled and hugged her. "Don't worry, Lily. I'll help you. This is not a regular orange. This is a special orange. It's called a grapefruit. It's bigger and sourer than an orange. You need a knife to cut it open."

She took Lily and the grapefruit to the kitchen. She cut the grapefruit in half and gave one half to Lily. She showed her how to use a spoon to scoop out the flesh. Lily tried it. It was not sweet like an orange. It was sour and bitter. She made a funny face and spit it out.

"Yuck! I don't like grapefruit!" she said.

Her mom laughed and kissed her. "That's okay, Lily. You don't have to like everything. Maybe you'll like it when you're older. Do you want a real orange instead?"

Lily nodded and smiled. "Yes, please. I love oranges. Thank you, mom."

Her mom gave her a small orange and helped her peel it. Lily ate it happily. It was sweet and juicy and made her mouth happy. She forgot about the grapefruit and the struggle. She was not confused and sad anymore. She was happy and loved.
<|end|>


