Sara liked to spend time with her grandma. Grandma was old and kind. She had white hair and a white cat. She also liked to read poems to Sara.

One day, Sara and Grandma were sitting on the couch. Grandma opened a big book and said, "This is a poem book. Poems are like songs, but you say them, not sing them. Do you want to hear a poem?"

Sara nodded. She liked poems. They made her feel happy and calm.

Grandma smiled and read a poem. It was about a snowman who had a hat and a scarf and a carrot nose. Sara listened and imagined the snowman. She wished she could make one.

When Grandma finished, she asked, "Did you like the poem, Sara?"

Sara nodded again. She said, "Yes, Grandma, I liked it very much. Can we make a snowman too?"

Grandma laughed and said, "Maybe when it snows, we can. But for now, we can draw one. Do you want to do that?"

Sara said, "Yes, please!" She ran to get some paper and crayons. She and Grandma drew a white snowman with a hat and a scarf and a carrot nose. They also drew a white cat and a big book. They wrote the poem under the picture.

Sara and Grandma were very proud of their drawing. They hung it on the fridge. They hugged and said, "We love poems and snowmen and each other!"
