<|asst|>
Lily and Ben were twins who liked to play with their big red ball. They would bounce it high in the air and catch it, or roll it to each other, or kick it across the yard. They had a lot of fun with their ball.

One day, they saw a shiny new automobile parked in front of their house. It was blue and had four doors and a big trunk. They wondered who it belonged to and what it was doing there.

"Let's go see it!" said Lily, grabbing the ball.

"OK, but be careful!" said Ben, following her.

They ran to the automobile and looked at it with curiosity. They touched the windows and the tires and the mirrors. They saw their faces reflected in the metal. They thought it was very pretty and different from their ordinary automobile, which was old and gray and had a dent in the side.

"Can we bounce the ball on it?" asked Lily, holding the ball.

"No, that's not nice!" said Ben, shaking his head. "It's not ours, and we might scratch it or break it. We should bounce the ball somewhere else."

But Lily didn't listen. She threw the ball as hard as she could on the roof of the automobile. The ball bounced back and hit her in the face. She cried out in pain and dropped the ball.

"Ow, ow, ow!" she wailed, rubbing her nose.

Ben ran to her and hugged her. He picked up the ball and put it in his pocket.

"I'm sorry, Lily, are you OK?" he asked, worried.

Lily nodded, still sniffling. She looked at the automobile and felt sorry too. She saw a small dent and a scratch on the roof where the ball had hit.

"Uh-oh, we're in trouble!" she said, scared.

Just then, the door of the house opened and a man came out. He was wearing a suit and a tie and had a briefcase in his hand. He walked to the automobile and saw the twins and the damage.

"Hey, what are you doing here? What did you do to my automobile?" he shouted, angry.

Lily and Ben were very afraid. They didn't know what to say or do. They wished they had listened to Ben and bounced the ball somewhere else. They learned a hard lesson that day.
<|end|>


