Ben and Mia were playing in the park with their ball. They liked to kick the ball to each other and run after it. Sometimes they missed the ball and it rolled away. They had to chase it before it got lost.

One time, the ball rolled very far and went into the bushes. Ben and Mia followed it, but they could not see it. They heard a splash and ran to the sound. They saw a big lake with water and fish and ducks. They had never seen the lake before. It was enormous!

"Wow!" Ben said. "Look at the lake! It is so big and blue!"

"Maybe our ball is in the lake," Mia said. "Can we find it?"

They looked around the lake, but they could not see their ball. They saw a lot of things in the lake, like rocks and plants and bubbles. They also saw something else. It was round and green and had eyes and teeth. It was a crocodile!

The crocodile saw Ben and Mia and opened its mouth. It was hungry and wanted to eat them. It swam towards them very fast. Ben and Mia were scared and screamed.

"Help! Help! A crocodile!" they shouted.

The crocodile was almost near them, when suddenly, a man appeared. He was wearing a hat and a vest and had a stick. He was a park ranger. He saw the crocodile and the children and ran to help them. He waved his stick and shouted at the crocodile.

"Go away! Go away! Leave the children alone!" he yelled.

The crocodile was afraid of the man and his stick. It turned around and swam away. It did not want to fight. Ben and Mia were safe. They hugged the park ranger and thanked him.

"Thank you, thank you, you saved us!" they said.

The park ranger smiled and patted their heads. He was glad they were okay.

"You're welcome, you're welcome, I'm glad you're okay," he said. "But you should not play near the lake. It is dangerous. There are crocodiles and other animals that can hurt you. You should stay in the playground where it is safe."

Ben and Mia nodded and agreed. They learned their lesson. They did not want to see the crocodile again. They asked the park ranger if he had seen their ball. He said he had. He had found it in the bushes and brought it with him. He gave it back to them.

"Here is your ball. Be careful with it. Don't let it roll away again," he said.

Ben and Mia thanked him again and took their ball. They ran back to the playground and played with it. They had fun and forgot about the lake and the crocodile. They only used simple words that a 3 year old child would understand. They were happy. The end.
<|end|>


