Anna and Ben like to play with blocks. They make big buildings with the blocks. They put windows and doors and roofs on the buildings. They pretend the buildings are houses or shops or schools.

One day, Anna and Ben have a fight. Anna wants to make a pink building. Ben wants to make a blue building. They do not want to share the blocks. They say mean words to each other.

"Go away, Ben! You are a bad boy!" Anna says.

"No, you go away, Anna! You are a bad girl!" Ben says.

They ignore each other. They turn their backs and make their own buildings. They do not look or talk to each other.

But then, a big noise makes them jump. It is a dog. The dog runs into the room. The dog sees the blocks. The dog thinks the blocks are toys. The dog knocks down the buildings with his paws and his tail. He makes a big mess.

"Hey, stop it, dog!" Anna says.

"Go away, dog!" Ben says.

But the dog does not listen. He keeps playing with the blocks. He bites and chews and throws the blocks.

Anna and Ben are sad. They see their buildings are gone. They see the blocks are broken. They see the dog is happy.

They look at each other. They feel sorry. They say sorry.

"I'm sorry, Ben. I was mean to you," Anna says.

"I'm sorry, Anna. I was mean to you," Ben says.

They hug each other. They forgive each other. They decide to play together. They pick up the blocks. They make a new building. They make a regular building. They make a building with pink and blue blocks. They make a building for them and for the dog. They are happy. They are friends.
<|end|>


