Lily liked to print poems on paper. She had a big book of poems that her mom gave her. She would pick a poem and copy the words with her crayon. Then she would draw a picture to go with the poem.

One day, she wanted to print a poem for her dad. He was at work and she missed him. She looked in her book and found a poem that said "I love you, dad". She thought it was perfect. She took a sheet of paper and started to print the words.

But when she finished, she saw that the paper was empty. She had used a white crayon on a white paper. She could not see the words or the picture. She felt sad and angry. She threw the paper on the floor and cried.

Her mom heard her cry and came to see what was wrong. She saw the empty paper and the white crayon. She hugged Lily and said, "What happened, sweetie?"

Lily told her mom what she wanted to do. She said, "I wanted to print a poem for dad, but it did not work. The paper is empty. I can't see the words or the picture. It's not fair!"

Her mom smiled and said, "I have an idea. Why don't we use a different crayon? A color that you can see on the paper. Then you can print the poem again and draw the picture. I'm sure your dad will love it."

Lily liked her mom's idea. She wiped her tears and picked a blue crayon. She printed the poem again and drew a heart and a flower. She was happy with her poem. She said, "Thank you, mom. You are the best. Can we give this to dad when he comes home?"

Her mom said, "Of course, we can. He will be so proud of you. You are a great poet, Lily." They hugged and waited for dad to come home.
