<|asst|>
Sara loves to play with her toy plane. It has two big wings and a long nose. It is a modern plane, not like the old ones in the books. Sara likes to make it fly in the air and zoom around the room.

One day, Sara takes her plane outside to the park. She wants to see how high it can go. She throws it up in the sky and watches it soar. She feels happy and proud. But then, a strong wind blows and takes her plane away. Sara runs after it, but it is too fast. She loses sight of it and feels sad and scared.

"Mommy, mommy, where is my plane?" Sara cries. She looks around, but she cannot find it. She thinks it is gone forever.

Mommy hugs Sara and tries to calm her down. She says, "Don't worry, sweetie, we will find your plane. Maybe someone saw it and will return it to us. Let's ask around and see if anyone knows where it is."

They walk around the park and ask the people they meet. Some of them saw the plane, but they do not know where it landed. Some of them did not see the plane, but they say they are sorry and hope Sara finds it. Sara feels a little better, but she still misses her plane.

Then, they hear a voice from a tree. It says, "Hey, is this your plane?" They look up and see a boy holding Sara's plane. He has a big smile on his face. He says, "I found it on a branch. It has a cool wing. It is a modern plane. Do you want it back?"

Sara feels very happy and excited. She says, "Yes, yes, that is my plane! Thank you, thank you, you are very nice!" She runs to the tree and reaches for her plane. The boy gives it to her and says, "You're welcome. I'm glad I could help. Have fun with your plane."

Sara hugs her plane and says, "I'm so happy I have you back. I love you, plane. You are the best." She smiles at the boy and says, "Thank you again. Do you want to play with me and my plane?"

The boy nods and says, "Sure, I would love to. What is your name?"

Sara says, "My name is Sara. What is yours?"

The boy says, "My name is Ben. Nice to meet you, Sara."

They become friends and play with the plane together. They make it fly and zoom and do tricks. They have a lot of fun. Mommy watches them and smiles. She is happy that Sara found her plane and made a new friend. She thinks it is a good day.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Lila and Sam were playing in the garden. They liked to look for bugs and flowers. They saw a big green caterpillar on a leaf. It had yellow and black stripes.

"Wow, look at that!" Sam said. "It is so big and pretty. Can I hold it?"

Lila shook her head. "No, Sam. It is my turn to choose a bug. You chose the ladybug before. That is fair."

Sam frowned. He wanted to hold the caterpillar too. He thought it was not fair. He said, "But I like caterpillars more than ladybugs. Please, Lila. Let me have it."

Lila thought for a moment. She liked caterpillars too. But she also liked to be fair. She said, "How about we share it? We can both hold it for a little bit. Then we can put it back on the leaf. OK?"

Sam nodded. He thought that was a good idea. He said, "OK, Lila. We can share it. Thank you for being fair."

Lila smiled. She said, "You are welcome, Sam. Thank you for being nice."

They carefully picked up the caterpillar and took turns holding it. They felt its soft and fuzzy body. They watched it wiggle and curl. They laughed and had fun. They were happy to share.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Tom and Ben were bad boys. They liked to take things that were not theirs. One day, they saw a big cake in a shop window. They wanted to eat the cake, so they broke the window and grabbed the cake. But a man saw them and called the police.

The police came and caught Tom and Ben. They put them in a car and took them to a place called jail. Jail was a big house with many rooms. But the rooms had bars on the windows and doors. The rooms were also filthy. There were bugs and dirt and bad smells. Tom and Ben did not like jail.

In jail, they had to stay in their room all day. They could not play or watch TV or read books. They only had bread and water to eat and drink. They were very sad and scared. They wished they had not taken the cake.

One day, a lady came to see them. She was their mom. She looked very angry and sad. She said to them, "Tom and Ben, you have been very naughty. You have to say sorry to the man and the shop. You have to pay for the window and the cake. You have to learn to be good boys. Do you understand?"

Tom and Ben nodded. They said, "Yes, mom. We are sorry. We will be good boys. We will not take things that are not ours. Please take us home."

The mom hugged them and said, "I love you, but you have to stay here for a little longer. The police will let you go soon. But you have to promise me to never do this again. Can you promise me?"

Tom and Ben said, "Yes, mom. We promise. We love you too."

The mom said, "Good. Now try to relax and be brave. I will come back to get you soon. Goodbye, my boys."

She left and Tom and Ben lay down on their bed. They felt a little better, but they still hated jail. They hoped they could go home soon and never come back. They learned their lesson. They closed their eyes and tried to relax.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Lily and Tom are playing a game. They have cards with pictures on them. They put the cards face down on the floor. They take turns to pick two cards and turn them over. If the cards have the same picture, they have a match. If not, they turn them back over.

Lily is nervous. She wants to win the game. She picks a card with a cat on it. She looks for another card with a cat. She sees one at the corner of the floor. She reaches for it.

"Wait!" Tom says. "That's my turn!"

Lily stops. She looks at Tom. He is angry. She feels bad. She says sorry.

Tom picks the card with the cat. He turns it over. It is a match. He smiles. He puts the cards in his pile.

Lily is sad. She has no matches. She has only one card left. She turns it over. It is a dog.

Tom has one card left too. He turns it over. It is a dog too. It is a match.

Lily and Tom look at each other. They are surprised. They have the same number of matches. They have tied the game.

They laugh. They are happy. They hug each other. They say good game.

They close the cards and put them away. They go to play something else. They are friends.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Lily and Ben were very hungry. They wanted to eat pizza for lunch. Mom said they could help her make pizza in the kitchen. Lily and Ben were happy.

Mom gave them some dough, sauce, cheese and toppings. She showed them how to roll the dough, spread the sauce, sprinkle the cheese and add the toppings. Lily and Ben had fun. They made their own pizzas with their favorite things. Lily put olives and mushrooms on hers. Ben put pepperoni and pineapple on his.

When they were done, Mom put the pizzas in the oven. She said they had to wait for a little while until the pizzas were cooked. Lily and Ben were impatient. They wanted to eat their pizzas right away.

"Mom, are the pizzas ready?" Lily asked.

"Not yet, sweetie. They need some more time. Why don't you play with your toys while we wait?" Mom said.

"Okay, Mom. Come on, Ben. Let's play with the blocks." Lily said.

Lily and Ben went to the living room. They found a big box of blocks. They decided to build a tower with the blocks. They worked together. They were gentle with the blocks. They did not knock them down or throw them. They wanted to make the tower as high as they could.

They were very proud of their tower. It was taller than them. They showed it to Mom.

"Wow, that's a great tower! You did a good job!" Mom said.

"Thank you, Mom. We worked hard. We were gentle." Lily said.

"Yes, you were. And guess what? The pizzas are ready! You can eat them now!" Mom said.

"Yay! Pizza time!" Ben said.

Lily and Ben ran to the kitchen. They saw their pizzas on the table. They smelled delicious. They thanked Mom for helping them make pizza. They cut their pizzas into slices. They ate their pizzas with big bites. They were very tasty. They were happy.

They had completed their lunch. They had completed their tower. They had completed their fun. They smiled at each other. They hugged Mom. They loved pizza. They loved blocks. They loved Mom.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Tim and Mia like to play with their toy trucks. They have many trucks of different colors and sizes. They make sounds like vroom and beep when they push them on the floor.

One day, they find a new truck in the toy box. It is big and red and has a button on the side. Tim presses the button and something shoots out of the truck. It is a small ball that flies across the room.

"Wow, look at that!" Tim says. "This truck can shoot balls!"

Mia wants to try too. She takes the truck from Tim and presses the button. Another ball shoots out and hits a lamp. The lamp falls and breaks with a loud crash.

"Oh no, we broke the lamp!" Mia says. "Mom will be mad!"

Tim and Mia are scared. They hide under the table with the truck and the balls. They hope Mom will not find out.

But Mom hears the noise and comes to see what happened. She sees the broken lamp and the balls on the floor. She is not happy.

"Who did this?" Mom asks. "Who broke the lamp?"

Tim and Mia peek out from under the table. They look at Mom with big eyes. They do not know what to say.

They are sorry they broke the lamp. They did not mean to. They just wanted to play with the lively truck that can shoot balls.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Lily and Max were playing outside. They liked to run and jump and make noise. They saw a big red mailbox on the street. They wanted to see what was inside.

"Let's open it!" said Max.

"No, we can't. It's not ours. It's for the mailman," said Lily.

"But I want to see. Maybe there are letters or pictures or stickers," said Max.

He tried to pull the mailbox open, but it was hard. It did not move. He pulled harder and harder, but it was still hard.

"Stop it, Max. You will break it. And the mailman will be sad," said Lily.

She grabbed his hand and pulled him away from the mailbox.

"Let's choose something else to play. We can play with the ball or the bike or the chalk," she said.

Max looked at the mailbox. He still wanted to see what was inside. But he also wanted to play with Lily. He liked Lily. She was his friend.

"Okay, Lily. I will choose something else. What do you want to play?" he said.

Lily smiled. She was happy that Max listened to her.

"I want to play with the chalk. We can draw pictures on the sidewalk. Maybe we can draw a mailbox and put our names on it," she said.

Max nodded. He liked that idea.

"Okay, Lily. Let's play with the chalk. Maybe the mailman will see our mailbox and give us a letter," he said.

They ran to get the chalk and started to draw. They had fun and forgot about the real mailbox. They were good friends.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Ben and Lily liked to play in the park. They liked to slide, swing, and run. But their favorite thing was to go to the tunnel. The tunnel was big and dark and fun. They liked to pretend they were explorers or pirates or spies.

One day, they found a shiny thing in the tunnel. It was round and metal and had a hole in it. Ben picked it up and said, "Look, Lily, I found a treasure!"

Lily looked at it and said, "What is it?"

Ben said, "I don't know. Maybe it's a coin or a medal or a button. Let's polish it and see."

They took the shiny thing to the fountain and rubbed it with water and their shirts. It became brighter and brighter. They saw some letters and numbers on it. They tried to read them, but they were too hard.

Suddenly, they heard a loud noise. It was a siren. They saw a big red truck with flashing lights. It stopped near the tunnel. Some men in yellow suits jumped out. They had hoses and helmets and axes. They ran to the tunnel and shouted, "Get away, kids! It's dangerous!"

Ben and Lily were scared. They dropped the shiny thing and ran to their mom. She hugged them and said, "What happened?"

The men in yellow suits came out of the tunnel. They had the shiny thing in their hands. They said, "We're sorry, kids, but you found a bomb. It was old and rusty and could have exploded. You're lucky we got here in time."

Ben and Lily gasped. They didn't know what a bomb was, but it sounded bad. They said, "We're sorry, too. We thought it was a treasure."

The men in yellow suits smiled and said, "Don't worry, kids. You're safe now. And you did find a treasure. A treasure of bravery and curiosity. Just be careful next time, OK?"

Ben and Lily nodded. They thanked the men in yellow suits and went home with their mom. They learned a new word that day: polish. And they learned that some things are not what they seem. And they learned that the tunnel was not always fun. Sometimes, it was dangerous.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Lily and Ben were twins who liked to play outside. One day, they saw a big, old mill near the river. It had a wide wheel that turned with the water. They wanted to go inside and see what was there.

"Can we go, Mom?" they asked.

"Okay, but be careful. Don't touch anything and stay together," Mom said.

Lily and Ben ran to the mill. They opened the door and saw many things. There were sacks of flour, big machines, and stairs to the top. They climbed the stairs and looked out of the window. They saw the river, the trees, and the sky.

"Wow, this is so cool!" Lily said.

"I wish we could live here," Ben said.

They lay down on the floor and closed their eyes. They dreamed of being the millers, making bread, and feeding the ducks. They dreamed of having fun and being happy.

They did not hear Mom calling them. They did not hear the thunder. They did not see the dark clouds.

They only woke up when the rain started to fall. They looked outside and saw the water rising. The river was angry and fast. The wheel was spinning and creaking.

"Mom! Mom!" they shouted.

"Help! Help!" they cried.

Mom heard them and ran to the mill. She saw them at the window and waved. She was scared and worried.

"Hold on, kids! I'm coming!" she said.

She found a rope and tied it to a tree. She threw the other end to the window. Lily and Ben grabbed it and climbed down. Mom hugged them and kissed them.

"Are you okay? Are you hurt?" she asked.

"We're okay, Mom. We're sorry. We were dreaming," they said.

Mom smiled and shook her head.

"Come on, let's go home. You can dream there, but not in the mill. The mill is not safe," she said.

Lily and Ben nodded and followed Mom. They looked back at the mill and saw the water reach the door. They felt sad and sorry.

"Goodbye, mill. Thank you for the dream," they said.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
