<|asst|>
Tom and Sam are friends. They like to play with cars and blocks. One day, Tom gets a new toy. It is a big truck with a chain. The chain can pull other cars and things.

Sam sees the truck and wants to play with it. He asks Tom, "Can I have a turn with your truck?"

Tom says, "No, it is mine. You have your own toys."

Sam feels envious. He thinks Tom is not nice. He says, "Your truck is not so good. My car is faster and prettier."

Tom does not answer. He does not care what Sam says. He likes his truck very much. He makes the truck go vroom vroom and beep beep.

Sam gets angry. He tries to grab the truck from Tom. Tom pulls the truck back. They start to fight. The chain breaks. The truck falls on the floor.

Tom and Sam both cry. They are sad and sorry. They broke the truck and hurt their friendship. They say, "I am sorry. Can we be friends again?"

They hug and make up. They share their toys and play together. They are happy and thankful. They learn to be kind and not envious.
<|end|>


<|sys|>
You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Lily liked to write stories with her crayons. She wrote about princesses, animals, and stars. One day, she decided to write a story about a pirate. She drew a big ship, a treasure chest, and a flag with a skull.

She also drew a pirate with a hat, a hook, and a patch. She made him very attractive, with a smile and a beard. She gave him a name: Jack. She wrote "Jack the pirate" under his picture.

She showed her story to her brother, Tom. Tom liked pirates too, but he did not like Lily's story. He said, "That is not a real pirate. Real pirates are mean and scary. They do not smile and have beards. They have scars and swords. And they do not have names like Jack. They have names like Blackbeard or Hook."

Lily was sad. She liked her story and her pirate. She said, "My pirate is real. He is nice and brave. He smiles and has a beard because he is happy and handsome. And he has a name like Jack because he is my friend."

Tom did not listen. He took Lily's story and tore it in half. He said, "This is a bad story. You do not know how to write pirates."

Lily cried. She ran to her mom and hugged her. She told her what Tom did. Mom was angry. She said, "Tom, that was very mean. You should not tear Lily's story. She worked hard on it. And you should not tell her how to write pirates. She can write whatever she wants. It is her imagination."

She took the pieces of Lily's story and taped them together. She said, "Lily, I am sorry. Your story is very good. I like your pirate. He is very attractive. And I like his name. Jack is a nice name for a pirate."

Lily smiled. She said, "Thank you, Mom. I love you. And I love Jack the pirate. He is my friend." She hugged her mom and her story. She did not care what Tom said. She was proud of her writing.
<|end|>


