<|asst|>
Lila liked to play soccer with her friends. She was very good at kicking the ball and making goals. She was independent and did not need help from anyone. She always wanted to win and have the highest score.

One day, she was playing soccer with Ben and Sam. They were on the same team and they were winning. Lila scored three goals and was very happy. But then, she saw that her ball had a hole in it. It was losing air and becoming flat. She was very sad and angry.

"Who did this to my ball?" she asked. "It was my favorite ball!"

Ben and Sam looked at the ball and felt sorry for Lila. They did not know who made the hole, but they wanted to help.

"Maybe we can repair it," Ben said. "We can use some tape and glue and make it round again."

"Or maybe we can share our ball with you," Sam said. "We have another ball that is good and bouncy. You can use it and we can still play together."

Lila thought about what Ben and Sam said. She liked their ideas, but she also liked her own ball. She did not want to give it up or use another one. She wanted to fix it and keep playing with it.

"Thank you, but no thank you," she said. "I can repair my ball by myself. I don't need your help or your ball. I am independent and I can do it alone."

She took her ball and walked away. She found some tape and glue and tried to repair the hole. But it was not easy. The tape did not stick and the glue did not dry. The ball was still flat and useless.

She looked at Ben and Sam. They were playing with their ball and having fun. They were still winning and scoring goals. They smiled and waved at her. They invited her to join them.

Lila felt lonely and silly. She realized that she was not independent. She needed her friends and their ball. She wanted to play and have fun with them. She wanted to share and be nice.

She picked up her ball and walked back to them. She apologized and asked if she could play with them.

"Of course you can," Ben and Sam said. "We are happy to share our ball with you. We are your friends and we want to play with you."

They gave her a hug and handed her the ball. Lila smiled and thanked them. She kicked the ball and scored a goal. They cheered and clapped for her. They played together and had a great time. Lila learned that being independent is good, but being friendly is better.
<|end|>


