Jack was feeling angry. He stomped his feet, he crossed his arms, and he made sure his mom saw his angry face. Jack wanted tuna for lunch, but his mom said no. She explained that too much tuna would make him sick. Still, Jack kept stomping, kept crossing his arms, and kept demanding tuna.

The mom didn't give in. She stood firm and said that she was preventing Jack from getting sick. Jack hated it, but he couldn't stop his mom. He didn't have a choice; he had to eat something else.

At first Jack was unhappy, but as time went on he began to feel better. He and his mom had lunch together and they talked and laughed. All the while, Jack forgotten his demand for tuna.

The next morning, when Jack woke up, he felt positively dizzy! He asked his mom what was wrong, and she reminded him of the tuna he wanted the day before! Jack had been so angry that he didn't realize he actually did get sick from the too much tuna he consumed.

Jack and his mom laughed at the realization, though it was a lesson well-learned. Jack promised to never be so angry again since he knew it wouldn't always prevent him from getting what he wants.
