Tom and Mia were playing in the backyard. They liked to pretend they were superheroes. Tom wore a red cape and Mia wore a blue one. They ran around and made noises like lasers and rockets.

"Look, there is a bad guy!" Tom said, pointing to a pile of laundry on the clothesline. "He wants to take our toys!"

"Let's stop him!" Mia said, and they ran towards the laundry. They pulled and tugged on the clothes, trying to make them fall.

But the laundry was too strong. It did not fall. It only made a loud noise. The noise was so loud that it made Mom come out of the house.

"What are you doing?" Mom asked, looking very sad. "You are ruining the laundry! It was clean and now it is dirty!"

Tom and Mia stopped playing. They felt bad. They did not want to make Mom sad.

"We are sorry, Mom," Tom said. "We were playing superheroes. We thought the laundry was a bad guy."

Mom sighed. She picked up the clothes and put them in a basket. "I know you were playing, but you have to be careful. The laundry is not a bad guy. It is just clothes. You have to respect them."

Tom and Mia nodded. They wanted to respect the clothes. They wanted to help Mom.

"Can we help you, Mom?" Mia asked. "Can we wash the clothes again?"

Mom smiled. She hugged them. "That is very kind of you. Yes, you can help me. But first, you have to believe me. The laundry is not a bad guy. It is just clothes. Do you believe me?"

Tom and Mia looked at each other. They thought for a moment. Then they nodded.

"Yes, Mom, we believe you," they said. "The laundry is not a bad guy. It is just clothes."

Mom smiled again. She took their hands and led them to the house. They went to wash the clothes again. They learned their lesson. They never played superheroes with the laundry again.
