Tom and Anna were playing in the park. They liked to run, jump and slide on the grass and the swings. They had fun with their friends and their toys.

But then, the sky became dark and the wind blew hard. They heard a loud noise like a big drum. It was thunder. They saw bright flashes like fire. It was lightning. They were scared and ran to their mom.

"Mom, mom, what is that?" Tom asked, holding his mom's hand.

"That is a storm, Tom. It is when the rain and the wind and the thunder and the lightning come together. It is noisy and bright, but it is not bad. It is just water and air and sound and light," mom said, hugging Tom and Anna.

"But mom, we are wet and cold. And our clothes are dirty. And our toys are still out there. What if they get lost or broken?" Anna said, looking at her black dress and her pink doll.

"Don't worry, Anna. We can dry and clean our clothes. And we can go back and get our toys when the storm is over. They will be fine. They are strong and brave, like you and Tom. And we are safe and warm, like our home. The storm will not last long. It will go away soon. And then we can see the sun and the rainbow and the birds again," mom said, smiling and kissing Anna and Tom.

Tom and Anna felt better. They trusted their mom. They stopped being scared and started being curious. They watched the storm from the window. They saw the rain and the wind and the thunder and the lightning. They learned new words and asked new questions. They were still wet and cold and dirty, but they were not worried. They were happy. They had each other and their mom. They had a stormy adventure.
<|end|>


