You are telling a short children's story.
<|end|>
<|asst|>
Sara and Ben like to play outside in the snow. They make a big snowman with a hat and a scarf. They give him a carrot nose and two rocks for eyes. They are very happy with their snowman.

But then they see a small insect on the snow. It is black and has six legs. It looks very cold and tired. Sara and Ben feel sorry for the insect.

"Hello, little insect," Sara says. "Are you lost? Do you need help?"

The insect does not answer. It shivers and tries to move.

"Maybe he is hungry," Ben says. "Let's find some food for him."

They look around and see some berries on a bush. They pick some and bring them to the insect. They put them near his mouth.

"Here, little insect," Ben says. "Eat some berries. They are sweet and juicy. They will make you feel better."

The insect looks at the berries. He smells them and nibbles on one. He likes the taste. He eats more and more. He feels warmer and stronger.

"Thank you, Sara and Ben," the insect says. "You are very kind and helpful. You encouraged me to eat and live."

Sara and Ben smile. They are glad the insect is happy.

"You are welcome, little insect," Sara says. "What is your name?"

"My name is Timmy," the insect says. "I am a beetle. I was looking for a place to sleep when the snow came. I got lost and scared."

"We can help you find a place to sleep," Ben says. "We know a cozy spot under a log. It is not icy there. It is warm and dry."

"Really?" Timmy says. "That would be wonderful. Can you show me the way?"

"Of course," Sara and Ben say. "Come with us, Timmy. We will be your friends."

They take Timmy by the legs and carry him to the log. They make a soft bed of leaves and grass for him. They tuck him in and say goodnight.

"Sleep well, Timmy," Sara and Ben say. "We will see you in the spring."

"Sleep well, Sara and Ben," Timmy says. "Thank you for everything. You are the best friends a beetle could have."

They hug and say goodbye. They go back to their snowman and wave to Timmy. They are happy they met him. They learned a lot from him. They learned to be kind, to share, and to encourage.
<|end|>


