Tom and Mia are friends. They like to play in the park. They see a big tree with many leaves. They want to know how big the tree is.

"Let's measure the tree!" Tom says. He takes a long rope from his backpack. He wraps the rope around the tree. He tries to touch the ends of the rope together. But the rope is too short. The tree is bigger than the rope.

"Wow, the tree is very big!" Mia says. She takes a small ruler from her pocket. She puts the ruler on the ground. She counts how many rulers it takes to go from the tree to the bench. She counts one, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten. The tree is ten rulers away from the bench.

"Wow, the tree is very far!" Tom says. He looks up at the tree. He sees a bird on a branch. The bird is singing a lively song. It has red and yellow feathers. It looks happy.

"Look, a bird!" Mia says. She points at the bird. She wants to see the bird closer. She takes a pair of binoculars from her backpack. She looks through the binoculars at the bird. She sees the bird's eyes, beak, and wings. The bird is very pretty.

"Wow, the bird is very pretty!" Tom says. He takes the binoculars from Mia. He looks through the binoculars at the bird. He sees the bird's feet, tail, and chest. The bird is very colorful.

"Can we touch the bird?" Mia asks. She likes the bird. She wants to be friends with the bird.

"I don't know," Tom says. He thinks the bird might be scared of them. He thinks the bird might fly away.

They decide to leave the bird alone. They say goodbye to the bird. They thank the bird for its song. They go to play on the swings. They have fun in the park. They are happy.
<|end|>


