Anna liked to dream. She dreamed of big fish and small fish, of red fish and blue fish, of fish that could talk and fish that could sing. She dreamed of swimming with them in the water, of playing with them and making friends.

One day, Anna went to the lake with her dad. He had a hook and a line, and he wanted to catch some fish. Anna did not like that. She did not want the fish to get hurt. She wanted them to be happy and free.

"Dad, why do you catch the fish?" she asked.

"Because they are tasty and good for us," he said. "Don't worry, they don't feel much pain. It's quick and easy."

Anna did not believe him. She thought the fish felt a lot of pain. She thought they were scared and sad. She did not want to eat them. She wanted to save them.

She waited until her dad was not looking. Then she took his hook and his line, and threw them into the water. She hoped the fish would see them and swim away.

"Anna, what did you do?" her dad shouted. He was angry and surprised. He ran to the water and tried to get his hook and his line back.

But it was too late. The fish had seen them and swam away. They were happy and free. They thanked Anna in their fishy way.

Anna smiled. She felt calm and good. She had made her dream come true. She had saved the fish.
