<|asst|>
Sara and Ben are friends. They like to play outside in the sun. One day, they find a big hill with green grass and yellow flowers. They want to go to the top of the hill.

"Let's skip to the tip!" Sara says. She holds Ben's hand and they start to skip. Skipping is fun. They feel happy and free.

They skip and skip and skip. They see birds and bugs and clouds. They laugh and sing and talk. They are almost at the tip of the hill.

But then, Ben trips on a rock. He falls down and hurts his knee. He cries and cries. He does not want to skip anymore.

Sara stops skipping. She sees Ben is sad and hurt. She runs to him and hugs him. She says, "I'm sorry, Ben. Are you OK?"

Ben sniffles and nods. He shows Sara his knee. It has a small cut and some blood. Sara says, "Don't worry, Ben. It's not bad. I have a band-aid in my pocket. I can put it on your knee. It will make it better."

Sara takes out a band-aid. It has a picture of a star on it. She sticks it on Ben's knee. She says, "There. Now you have a star on your knee. You are brave and strong."

Ben smiles and says, "Thank you, Sara. You are kind and sweet."

Sara says, "You're welcome, Ben. You are my friend. Do you want to skip to the tip again?"

Ben says, "Yes, I do. But can we go slow and careful?"

Sara says, "Of course we can. We can go as slow and careful as you want. We can also stop and rest if you need."

Ben says, "OK. That sounds good. That sounds comfortable."

Sara says, "Yes, it does. It sounds comfortable and fun."

They hold hands again and start to skip. They skip slow and careful. They skip to the tip of the hill. They see the sun and the sky and the world. They feel happy and free. They are friends.
<|end|>


