Tim and Liz are playing in their room. It is very hot today. They have a fan, but it is broken. The fan does not spin or make wind.

"Mom, can you fix the fan?" Tim asks. He is sweaty and thirsty.

"I'm sorry, Tim. I don't know how to fix the fan. Maybe we can buy a new one later." Mom answers. She is busy in the kitchen.

Liz has an idea. She finds some paper and scissors. She cuts the paper into shapes. She makes a star, a heart, a circle, and a square. She tapes the shapes to the fan.

"Look, Tim. I made the fan pretty." Liz says. She is proud of her work.

Tim looks at the fan. He smiles. He likes the shapes. He turns on the fan. The fan still does not spin or make wind. But the shapes flap and flutter.

"Wow, Liz. You made the fan fun." Tim says. He claps his hands.

They play with the fan. They pretend the shapes are flying. They have fun. They forget about the heat.
