<|asst|>
Tommy did not like haircuts. They made his head feel funny and the scissors were loud. He hid under his bed when Mommy said it was time to go to the barber. Mommy looked for him everywhere. She called his name, but he was quiet.

"Tommy, where are you?" Mommy asked. "We have to go now. The barber is waiting for us."

Tommy did not answer. He hoped Mommy would forget about the haircut. He closed his eyes and hugged his teddy bear.

But Mommy did not forget. She found him under the bed. She pulled him out gently and smiled.

"Come on, Tommy. It's not so bad. The haircut will make you look handsome and cool. And the barber is very nice. He will give you a sticker and a lollipop when he is done."

Tommy frowned. He did not want to look handsome and cool. He liked his hair the way it was. And he did not care about stickers and lollipops. He wanted to stay home and play with his toys.

"Please, Mommy. No haircut. I don't like it. It hurts and it's scary."

Mommy hugged him and kissed his cheek.

"I know, Tommy. But haircuts are good for you. They keep your hair clean and healthy. And they don't hurt or scare you. The barber is gentle and careful. He will talk to you and make you laugh. And I will be right there with you. I promise."

Tommy looked at Mommy. He saw that she was not angry or mean. She was kind and loving. He trusted her. He sighed and nodded.

"Okay, Mommy. I will go with you. But can I bring my teddy bear?"

Mommy nodded and smiled.

"Of course, Tommy. You can bring your teddy bear. He can have a haircut too, if you want."

Tommy smiled a little. He took his teddy bear and held Mommy's hand. They went to the car and drove to the barber. Tommy was still nervous, but he was brave. He hoped the haircut would be over soon. And he hoped he would get a nice sticker and a lollipop.
<|end|>


