<|asst|>
Sam and Mia are twins. They like to play with their toys and make noise. But today, they are not feeling well. Their stomachs hurt and they feel hot.

"Mia, I want to give you my teddy bear. He makes me happy when I am sick," Sam says.

"Thank you, Sam. You are a good brother. I want to give you my doll. She sings a nice song when you press her tummy," Mia says.

They hug each other and share their toys. They hope they will get better soon.

But then, they hear a loud knock on the door. It is their mom. She has a big bag of groceries.

"Hello, my loves. I am back from the store. I bought you some soup and crackers. They will help your stomachs feel better," she says.

She puts the bag on the table and goes to check on them. She sees them lying on the couch with their toys.

"Oh, you are so sweet. You are sharing your toys. How are you feeling?" she asks.

"We are feeling a little better, mom. But our stomachs still hurt," they say.

"I am sorry, my loves. Let me take your temperature and give you some medicine. Then, you can have some soup and crackers," she says.

She takes a thermometer and puts it in their mouths. She sees that they have a fever.

"You have a fever, my loves. You need to rest and drink a lot of water. Here, take this medicine. It will make you feel better," she says.

She gives them each a spoonful of medicine. They make a face. The medicine tastes bad.

"Yuck, mom. The medicine is yucky," they say.

"I know, my loves. But it is good for you. It will make your fever go away. Now, let me make you some soup and crackers. They will be yummy," she says.

She goes to the kitchen and heats up the soup. She pours it into two bowls and adds some crackers. She brings them to the couch.

"Here you go, my loves. Some soup and crackers. Be careful, they are hot. Blow on them before you eat them," she says.

She gives them each a bowl and a spoon. They blow on the soup and eat it slowly. The soup and crackers are yummy. They make their stomachs feel warm and cozy.

"Thank you, mom. The soup and crackers are yummy. They make our stomachs feel better," they say.

"You are welcome, my loves. I am glad you like them. You are very brave and strong. I am proud of you," she says.

She kisses them on their foreheads and sits with them. She reads them a story and sings them a lullaby. They cuddle with their toys and close their eyes. They fall asleep.

Their mom smiles and covers them with a blanket. She hopes they will get better soon. She loves them very much.

The end.
<|end|>


