Tom and Lily liked to play near the lake. They saw a fisherman with a big hat and a long stick. He threw a string into the water and waited.

"Can we watch him?" Lily asked Tom.

"OK, but we have to be quiet," Tom said. "He is trying to catch fish."

They sat on the grass and looked at the fisherman. He was very alert. He watched the string and felt the stick. Sometimes he smiled and sometimes he frowned.

"What is he doing?" Lily whispered.

"He is guessing," Tom whispered back. "He is guessing if there is a fish on the string or not. If there is, he will pull the stick and get the fish. If not, he will throw the string again."

They watched for a long time. The fisherman guessed right and wrong many times. He caught some fish and put them in a basket. He missed some fish and shook his head.

"Wow, he is good at guessing," Lily said.

"Yes, he is," Tom agreed. "But I think we are better at guessing."

"How?" Lily asked.

"Let's guess how many fish he has in his basket," Tom said. "I guess five."

"I guess six," Lily said.

They got up and walked to the fisherman. They smiled and said hello.

"Hello, kids," the fisherman said. "Do you like fishing?"

"Yes, we do," Tom and Lily said.

"We were watching you," Tom said. "You are very good at guessing."

"Thank you," the fisherman said. "But how do you know that?"

"We were guessing too," Lily said. "We were guessing how many fish you have in your basket."

"Really?" the fisherman said. "And how many do you think I have?"

Tom and Lily said their guesses. The fisherman laughed and opened his basket.

"Let's see," he said. "One, two, three, four, five, six, seven. I have seven fish. You are both very close, but Lily is closer. She guessed six."

"Yay, I win!" Lily said.

"Good job, Lily," Tom said.

The fisherman gave them each a fish to take home. They thanked him and said goodbye. They ran back to their house, happy and proud. They had fun guessing with the fisherman.
<|end|>


