Lily liked to wander in the park with her mom. She saw many things that made her happy. She saw flowers, birds, dogs, and swings. She liked to smell the flowers, hear the birds, pet the dogs, and ride the swings.

One day, she saw something new in the park. It was shiny and big and had a star on top. It was a trophy. Lily wondered who it belonged to. She wanted to touch it and see how it felt. She ran to the trophy and reached for it.

But before she could touch it, a boy came and shouted at her. He said, "Hey, that's mine! Don't touch it! I won it in a race!" He grabbed the trophy and held it tight. He looked angry and mean.

Lily felt sad and scared. She did not mean to make the boy mad. She just wanted to see the trophy. She ran back to her mom and hugged her. She told her what happened.

Her mom said, "I'm sorry, Lily. That was not nice of him. He should have shared his trophy with you. But you know what? You don't need a trophy to be special. You are special because you are kind, curious, and brave. You are my trophy, and I love you very much."

Lily felt glad and warm. She smiled and said, "I love you too, mom. You are my trophy too." She kissed her mom and hugged her again. She forgot about the boy and the trophy. She was happy in the park with her mom.
<|end|>


