Tom and Anna are going on a trip with Mom and Dad. They are very happy. They want to see new things and play with new friends. But first, they have to pack their bags and get ready.

Mom tells them to sort their toys and clothes. She says they can only take some, not all. Tom and Anna have to choose. They put their favorite toys and clothes in their bags. They leave the rest in their room.

Then, Mom gives them each a passport. She says it is a very important paper. It has their name and picture on it. It tells who they are and where they are from. She says they have to keep it safe and show it to the people at the airport.

Tom and Anna look at their passports. They see their faces and names. They feel proud. They put their passports in their bags, too.

They are ready to go. They carry their bags to the car. Dad puts them in the trunk. He says they have to hurry. They don't want to miss their plane.

They get in the car and buckle their seat belts. They drive to the airport. They see many cars and buses and people. They see tall buildings and big signs. They are excited.

They get to the airport. They take their bags and passports. They follow Mom and Dad. They see a long line of people. They have to wait. They are bored.

They hear a loud voice. It says, "Next, please." They look up. They see a man behind a desk. He is wearing a uniform and a hat. He is very tall. He has a scanner and a stamp. He is checking the passports.

Mom and Dad give him their passports. He scans them and stamps them. He says, "Have a nice trip." He gives them back their passports.

Then, he looks at Tom and Anna. He smiles. He says, "Hello, little travelers. Can I see your passports, too?"

Tom and Anna give him their passports. He scans them and stamps them. He says, "Wow, you have very nice passports. You are very lucky. Where are you going?"

Tom and Anna say, "We are going to France. We want to see the Eiffel Tower and eat croissants."

The man says, "That sounds wonderful. I hope you have a lot of fun. Here are your passports. Keep them safe. Have a nice trip."

He gives them back their passports. He waves at them. Tom and Anna wave back. They say, "Thank you, sir. Goodbye."

They follow Mom and Dad. They go to the gate. They board the plane. They find their seats. They put their bags and passports in the overhead bin. They sit down and buckle their seat belts.

They are ready to fly. They are very happy. They are going on a trip.
<|end|>


